data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overload resolution rules cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (the span-based overload) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix it

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the LINQ overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

This same issue affects `Reverse()` on arrays (resolves to the in-place `Span` version instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`). The fix pattern is the same: disambiguate with `.AsEnumerable()`, a cast, or an explicit static call.
